The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                        NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 Srinagar, Feb. 6 (PTI): The district administration has asked local news channels to desist from airing provocative and anti-government footage in their current affairs and news programmes.          
	The direction for self-censorship has been given under Section 6 of the Cable TV Regulation Act, 2005, under which airing of anti-government content amounts to breach of peace and tranquillity of the general public. The directions came after local channels telecast the footage of violent clashes between people and police following the death of a teenager on Sunday.                  
	 New Delhi (PTI): A Delhi court framed charges on Saturday against four persons for alleged forgery, cheating and illegal tapping of former Samajwadi Party leader Amar Singhs phone in 2005.                   
	 Mainpuri (PTI): Six primary school teachers in Uttar Pradesh have been sacked for truancy while notices have been served on eight others for remaining absent from duty for a long time, an official said on Saturday. The move follows surprise school inspections as part of a drive to check the attendance of primary school teachers.                   
	 Mumbai (PTI): The chairman and director of City Limouzines, a company which allegedly duped over 25,000 investors across the country out of crores of rupees by floating a scheme, were remanded in police custody for 11 days on Saturday, police said.                   
	 Rajahmundry (PTI): Show-cause notices have been issued to 20 social welfare officials for their failure to maintain proper sanitation facilities in social welfare hostels in east Godavari district in Andhra Pradesh, authorities said on Saturday .                   
	 Jammu (PTI): A suspected smuggler was arrested on Saturday with a leopard skin. Police, posing as customers, reached Gujjar Colony and arrested Mohmmad Hanief as soon as he fixed the deal for Rs 70,000 and handed over the leopard skin to them.
                                                                                                                                              
